    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "targeted_sweep8_lite_2016_retarget",
    "description": "Lite network equivalence validation at realistic 2016-block difficulty retarget intervals. Companion to targeted_sweep5 (which validated equivalence at 144-block retarget).\nAll prior targeted sweeps use an accelerated 144-block retarget (~5 min per adjustment at 2-second block intervals). The 2016-block retarget (~67 min) creates qualitatively different dynamics:\n\n  - Minority chain difficulty adjustment takes ~14x longer wall-clock time\n  - The survival window is much wider \u2014 more time for price to collapse before the\n    adjustment arrives, but also a larger difficulty drop when it does\n  - Fee counter-pressure is sustained much longer, partially compensating miners\n    on the minority chain during the extended penalty period\n  - The difficulty adjustment profit spike (see \"Difficulty Adjustment Survival\n    Window\" in SWEEP_FINDINGS.md) is larger and more abrupt\n\nThese dynamics may interact differently with the lite network's consolidated economic cohorts vs the full network's individual entity representation. Specifically, the longer window gives economic nodes more decision cycles before the adjustment, potentially amplifying or dampening the cascade differently at each network size.\nThis sweep uses the same economic_split grid as targeted_sweep5 and the same fixed parameters as targeted_sweep1, enabling a three-way comparison:\n  targeted_sweep1  (full, 144-block):  v26, v26, v26, v26, v27\n  targeted_sweep5  (lite, 144-block):  v26, v26, v26, v26, v27  [confirmed match]\n  targeted_sweep8  (lite, 2016-block): run to find out\n\nIf the outcomes match across all three, the lite network is cleared for use in any 2016-block retarget studies and Phase 3 can proceed on either network at either retarget interval. If they diverge, the divergence will reveal which retarget regime is sensitive to network size.\nIMPORTANT \u2014 Runtime parameter: This sweep requires a non-default retarget interval. Pass --retarget-interval 2016 when running step 3:\n\n  python3 tools/sweep/3_run_sweep.py \\\n    --input targeted_sweep8_lite_2016_retarget/build_manifest.json \\\n    --duration 1800 --interval 2 \\\n    --retarget-interval 2016\n\nNote: At 2-second block intervals and 2016-block retarget, each adjustment occurs every ~4,032 seconds (~67 min). With 1800-second runs, the minority chain (25% hashrate) produces ~225 blocks per run \u2014 well short of a full retarget cycle. The majority chain produces ~675 blocks. This means difficulty does NOT adjust during the run, and all dynamics play out under the original inherited pre-fork difficulty. This is actually the most realistic scenario: the fork is young and neither chain has retargeted yet. Extend --duration to 7200 (2 hours) or more to capture the first retarget event on the majority chain.\nRecommended duration: 7200 seconds (2 hours) to capture at least one majority-chain retarget and the beginning of the minority chain's extended struggle.\nRuntime estimate: ~5 scenarios \u00d7 ~60-120 min = ~5-10 hours on lite network (longer per scenario due to extended duration).\n",
